NSTextField (Just type how many minutes you want the timer on (write "1.5" for one and a half minute for example). It also supports the minute:seconds format so "1:30" is one minute and 30 seconds (same as "1.5"). Note that you can leave out the minute part altogether like so: ":10" (for ten seconds). After writing the time you can add a description by pressing space and then typing any string you want. This string will be spoken aloud when the timer runs out and if you have growl installed it will use this in the notification. You can just press enter to start a timer instead of clicking the start button. Note that the focus is still in the text input control after this so you can instantly add another timer.) : <title:Just type how many minutes you want the timer on (write "1.5" for one and a half minute for example). It also supports the minute:seconds format so "1:30" is one minute and 30 seconds (same as "1.5"). Note that you can leave out the minute part altogether like so: ":10" (for ten seconds).
After writing the time you can add a description by pressing space and then typing any string you want. This string will be spoken aloud when the timer runs out and if you have growl installed it will use this in the notification.
You can just press enter to start a timer instead of clicking the start button. Note that the focus is still in the text input control after this so you can instantly add another timer.> (oid:313)

Just type how many minutes you want the timer on (write "1.5" for one and a half minute for example). It also supports the minute:seconds format so "1:30" is one minute and 30 seconds (same as "1.5"). Note that you can leave out the minute part altogether like so: ":10" (for ten seconds).
After writing the time you can add a description by pressing space and then typing any string you want. This string will be spoken aloud when the timer runs out and if you have growl installed it will use this in the notification.
You can just press enter to start a timer instead of clicking the start button. Note that the focus is still in the text input control after this so you can instantly add another timer.

Just type how many minutes you want the timer on (write "1.5" for one and a half minute for example). It also supports the minute:seconds format so "1:30" is one minute and 30 seconds (same as "1.5"). Note that you can leave out the minute part altogether like so: ":10" (for ten seconds).
After writing the time you can add a description by pressing space and then typing any string you want. This string will be spoken aloud when the timer runs out and if you have growl installed it will use this in the notification.
You can just press enter to start a timer instead of clicking the start button. Note that the focus is still in the text input control after this so you can instantly add another timer.

Skriv bara in hur många minuter du vill ha en timer på (skriv t.ex. "1,5" för en och en halv minut). Timer stödjer också minute:sekund-format så "1:30" är en minut och trettio sekunder. Du kan uteslutat minut-sidan helt så ":10" blir tio sekunder.
Efter du skrivit tiden kan du lägga till en beskrivning av timern genom att trycka mellanslag och sen skriva vad du vill. Det du skriver här kommer stå på timern, sägas högt vid slutet av tiden och om du har Growl installerat så kommer denna text visas där också.
Du kan trycka enter för att starta en timer istället för att klicka på startknappen.
